This paper deals with auction theory and mechanism design, which are typically studied in the computer science subfield of game theory (cs.GT). The paper also involves approximation algorithms, which are commonly studied in theoretical computer science (cs.DS). The use of private signals and valuation functions suggests a connection to machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The study of welfare maximization and revenue optimization falls under the umbrella of algorithmic mechanism design (cs.EC). Finally, the paper involves information theory, as it considers the impact of private signals on valuations (cs.IT).
